00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:45.540
And I think that really
all over the world,

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:48.060
people are looking for the new.

00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:50.510
They're looking for
great ethnic food,

00:07:50.510 --> 00:07:55.450
and that's what we
really love so much.

00:07:55.450 --> 00:07:58.540
And that's why there's so many new,

00:07:58.540 --> 00:08:04.580
exciting restaurants
from all over the world.

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:07.090
Thank you for doing this.

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:15.860
So what -- the way that this
book started was I had written --

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:20.270 position:56%
I had written a proposal for another
book, which was to be something

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:22.190
on modern Jewish cooking.

00:08:22.190 --> 00:08:25.100
And I really wasn't that
interested in doing it,

00:08:25.100 --> 00:08:27.500
but I don't think I ever
admitted it to myself.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:36.520
So I took a trip to
India, and I was in Kochi,

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:38.620
which is, you know, Cochin.

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:42.680
And I went to a synagogue
there, and on the wall it said

00:08:42.680 --> 00:08:48.030
that Jews had been there since
the time of King Solomon.

00:08:48.030 --> 00:08:53.490
And I started thinking, wow,
since the time of King Solomon?

00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:56.660
And so, I looked at
when King Solomon was.

00:08:56.660 --> 00:09:00.170
It was about 1,000 BC if
there was a King Solomon.

00:09:00.170 --> 00:09:01.700
There are two schools of thought.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:05.090
There are some people who
think that he's really a myth,

00:09:05.090 --> 00:09:09.170
and the myth of the one -- you
know, the wise man and the king

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:10.650
and that really there was no --

00:09:10.650 --> 00:09:13.460
I mean I don't see how they can
think there was no first temple,

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:14.760
but they do.

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.580
Other people think that he was --

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:20.520
he did exist, and I'm
going to be with those.

00:09:20.520 --> 00:09:23.610
Anyway, he's a great metaphor for
all that's wonderful and somebody

00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:26.920
who really likes good food.

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:30.040
So what I did was I looked when --

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:37.050
1,000 BC, and I went straight to
an archaeologist named Eric Klein,

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:39.870
who many of you might know from GW.

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:43.800
And he said to me, why
don't you come with me

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:49.900
to an archaeological conference
in Baltimore, which I did.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:53.450
And I met all the leading
archaeologists,

00:09:53.450 --> 00:09:57.710
and they told me what
they've been finding on food.

00:09:57.710 --> 00:10:01.380
And everybody told me to
read a book by Jean Bottero

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:06.030
on the oldest cuisine in
the world, which I did read.

00:10:06.030 --> 00:10:11.860
It was from 1700 BCE,
and the book was --

00:10:11.860 --> 00:10:20.460
the book was on a cuneiform tablet
written in Acadian on four tablets

00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:28.630
that are all at the Sterling
Library at Yale University.

00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:36.000
And the tablets had a -- these
44 recipes, but most of them were

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.780
for huge amounts of food.

00:10:38.780 --> 00:10:41.120
And they were for the
gods because they were --

00:10:41.120 --> 00:10:43.860
everybody believed in
gods in those days.

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:47.800 position:56%
And -- but what was interesting for
me, there were -- mostly were stews.

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:49.640
There were some breads.

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:54.000
You couldn't really tell
what the recipes were.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.370
But there was one recipe
for -- thank you --

00:10:57.370 --> 00:11:00.040
for a soup, a borscht soup.

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:04.500
And then there were all
these other recipes.

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:08.800
And what I was interested,
what the ingredients were.

00:11:08.800 --> 00:11:11.560
So if you look at the top of the --

00:11:11.560 --> 00:11:17.040
the cover of the book right
there and you can see a bread.

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:21.280
It's an Ethiopian Sabbath bread.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:25.950
And it's got these little
seeds on it, Nigella seeds,

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:29.600
that we're all rediscovering now.

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:34.580
But these are some of the
oldest seeds known to man.

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:37.180
Then there was sesame seeds.

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:40.060
Sesame seeds, if sesame
seeds were existing then,

00:11:40.060 --> 00:11:43.350
it meant that sesame seeds
came from China already

00:11:43.350 --> 00:11:48.280
and that they're the
first ground seed oil.

00:11:48.280 --> 00:11:54.220
So they were ground into oil I'm
assuming, and if they were ground

00:11:54.220 --> 00:11:56.690
into oil, you can bet
that another ingredient

00:11:56.690 --> 00:11:58.360
that was there was chickpeas.

00:11:58.360 --> 00:12:00.820
The chickpea, the hummus was there.

00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:03.340
It wasn't as a recipe in this list,

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:05.920
but this was something
that was a gruel.

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:10.160
That's what everybody ate,
but as a gruel with protein

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:15.800
so that people ate that for
morning and very often for evening,

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:20.650
poor people especially, as they
still do in the Middle East.

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:25.540
And one thing that I've learned
since I've worked on the book was

00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:30.620
that chickpeas have been around
for about 12,000 years in the area

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:33.670
so that everybody had hummus,

00:12:33.670 --> 00:12:38.280
in case you're not aware
of the hummus wars.

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:45.410
Every single country had hummus,
and the Proverbs of Gilgamesh,

00:12:45.410 --> 00:12:48.510
which are from about the same time,
and nobody's sure exactly when,

00:12:48.510 --> 00:12:55.760
but they're certainly a lot
earlier than the 1700 BCE cookbook.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:58.210
They mentioned chickpea flour,

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:01.280
and chickpea flour was what you
would have used in the winter.

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:04.740
And of course, now
everybody's so excited

00:13:04.740 --> 00:13:08.220
because everybody that's
gluten-free is suddenly eating

00:13:08.220 --> 00:13:09.670
chickpea pancakes.

00:13:09.670 --> 00:13:14.320
And they think that they're 19th
century Italian called farinata

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:20.010
or they're 19th century
French called soca.

00:13:20.010 --> 00:13:22.170
But they've been around
for thousands of years.

00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:25.220
And so, I began to
realize a few things.

00:13:25.220 --> 00:13:28.930
First of all, the timeline
of Judaism, you know, whether

00:13:28.930 --> 00:13:34.280 position:56%
or not it's exact is something else,
but also the timeline of foods.

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:36.220
There were -- I said
there were beets.

00:13:36.220 --> 00:13:37.850
There were Swiss chard.

00:13:37.850 --> 00:13:41.290
There were -- well, there's dill.

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:44.390
There were lots of
ingredients that were used then.

00:13:44.390 --> 00:13:46.960
And the sesame seeds
made me realize --

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:52.970
well, something else
that an academic at --

00:13:52.970 --> 00:14:01.350 position:56%
no, the archivist of the Sterling
Library told me was that the plates,

00:14:01.350 --> 00:14:06.010
the -- there were blue and white
plates from China, the same pattern

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:09.600 position:56%
in China as in Cypress at that time.

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:15.640
So plates were going around, and
these blue and white also might --

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:19.950
we -- it's a surmise,
but probably is correct.

00:14:19.950 --> 00:14:22.330
At some point, they were made in --

00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:25.830
I know they were made
in Iraq or Babylonia.

00:14:25.830 --> 00:14:32.040
Then they went north and eventually
came to Scandinavia, where they --

00:14:32.040 --> 00:14:37.530
to this day, there's blue
and white Scandinavian china.

00:14:37.530 --> 00:14:40.680
But what else went from Babylonia?

00:14:40.680 --> 00:14:42.300
Cardamom went with it.

00:14:42.300 --> 00:14:46.930
And so, cardamom appears in
cakes throughout Scandinavia

00:14:46.930 --> 00:14:51.760
because I always think that the
spices are a byproduct really

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:54.210
or something easily
that you can carry

00:14:54.210 --> 00:14:57.890
when you're shipping big things.

00:14:57.890 --> 00:14:59.990
Anyway, so I looked at that.

00:14:59.990 --> 00:15:03.290
Then I realized that
about 1,000 BCE,

00:15:03.290 --> 00:15:06.870
there was this man named
Abraham, who lived in Or,

00:15:06.870 --> 00:15:10.070
which isn't that far
away from Babylonia.

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:11.370
How many miles?

00:15:11.370 --> 00:15:15.600
She knows by heart,
about 300 miles I think.

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:22.610
Anyway, and so Abraham, remember
he took the idols and broke them.

00:15:22.610 --> 00:15:24.100
He was a monotheist.

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:29.990
And so, he went on to the land of
Canaan with his people, with his --

00:15:29.990 --> 00:15:36.880
I think he was sort of one of
the early communes with his wife,

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:40.660
his cousins, his friends,
and they set up --

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:43.650
they moved to the land of Canaan.

00:15:43.650 --> 00:15:47.010
And then we know from the Bible
the foods that he found there,

00:15:47.010 --> 00:15:51.650
which I'm sure he had
early on in the land of --

00:15:51.650 --> 00:15:56.910
in Babylonia because this was
the Tigris and Euphrates were

00:15:56.910 --> 00:16:03.310
in the Fertile Crescent, and
there was so much growing there.

00:16:03.310 --> 00:16:09.080
So he went and he found these seven
ingredients in the land of Canaan.

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:17.020 position:56%
He found barley, wheat, figs, dates,
olives, grapes, and pomegranates.

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:19.600
In addition, he found chickpeas.

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:23.240
He found lentils.

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:26.020
And he probably found fava
beans, although they --

00:16:26.020 --> 00:16:28.170
well, he would have
found them by then.

00:16:28.170 --> 00:16:36.310
So these were things that -- basic
foods that people had at that time.

00:16:36.310 --> 00:16:42.890
And I also realized that when the
Jews went, of course, to Egypt,

00:16:42.890 --> 00:16:47.160
then they came back and
built the first temple,

00:16:47.160 --> 00:16:52.070
which was with King
Solomon, after King David.

00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:56.460
And the reason that I call the book
King Solomon's Table were a number

00:16:56.460 --> 00:16:57.760
of things.

00:16:57.760 --> 00:17:02.940
First of all, in the Book of
Kings, it says that the 12 tribes

00:17:02.940 --> 00:17:09.220
of Israel had to tie -- were
tithed or had to tithe the king,

00:17:09.220 --> 00:17:17.100
King Solomon, with foods and also
jewels and stones and peacocks,

00:17:17.100 --> 00:17:20.150
which they got -- I know that that
was one of the things they got.

00:17:20.150 --> 00:17:22.950
And it was written from India

00:17:22.950 --> 00:17:25.770
that they found them
as far East as India.

00:17:25.770 --> 00:17:30.790 position:56%
So each month of the year, there was
one group that was tithing the king.

00:17:30.790 --> 00:17:35.230
In addition, King Solomon,
who as we all know was wise,

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:38.180
he also certainly had appetites.

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:44.110 position:56%
He had 700 wives and 300 concubines.

00:17:44.110 --> 00:17:49.770
So each of these women would
have brought with her food.

00:17:49.770 --> 00:17:51.760
I mean there probably were not 700.

00:17:51.760 --> 00:17:55.290
But anyway, that's why some
people think he doesn't exist.

00:17:55.290 --> 00:17:57.130
You know, it's too many wives.

00:17:57.130 --> 00:18:03.120
Anyway, but if you go to a Buddhist
temple anywhere in the East,

00:18:03.120 --> 00:18:08.380
you see the temple or
the kingdom up top,

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:12.640
and then in the front you'll
see places for the concubines.

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:15.330
And I realized it was a
sign of power to have lots

00:18:15.330 --> 00:18:19.830
of wives and lots of concubines.

00:18:19.830 --> 00:18:26.290
Anyway, so to me King Solomon, his
wives brought in all the spices,

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:29.580
all the different foods, because
you would bring that from home.

00:18:29.580 --> 00:18:30.880
Wouldn't you?

00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:32.180
You would bring what
you were familiar

00:18:32.180 --> 00:18:34.190
with if you were going
someplace new.

00:18:34.190 --> 00:18:40.400
And so, there were all kinds of
flavors going on at his -- in --

00:18:40.400 --> 00:18:45.160
at his temple and also at his
palace, which was also on the --

00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:50.590
you know, it was on the
Mount, the Temple Mount.

00:18:50.590 --> 00:18:55.900 position:56%
And I also knew from the Phoenicians
that the Jews learned how

00:18:55.900 --> 00:18:58.210
to use day boats, which
were wooden boats.

00:18:58.210 --> 00:19:01.650
And they would have been
young boys probably.

00:19:01.650 --> 00:19:04.670 position:56%
I don't think anybody else would
have done this, that would have gone

00:19:04.670 --> 00:19:09.650
out and have gone as far as
India and went -- was near --

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:14.340
were near India, and they would
see all the different foods

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:19.740
that were growing right
on like the ginger

00:19:19.740 --> 00:19:21.930
and the cardamom and the pepper.

00:19:21.930 --> 00:19:25.860
So they'd see these spices
that were so valuable

00:19:25.860 --> 00:19:28.020
and also were transportable.

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:29.350
And they would gather them.

00:19:29.350 --> 00:19:31.280 position:56%
Some of them would meet women there.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:35.240
They'd marry them, or they'd at
least have children with them.

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:36.540
And they would stay.

00:19:36.540 --> 00:19:37.840
Others would leave.

00:19:37.840 --> 00:19:41.220
In the 12th century, one of those
little villages that I went to,

00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:44.220
Shanondaglom [assumed
spelling] I think it's called,

00:19:44.220 --> 00:19:45.770
there was a synagogue.

00:19:45.770 --> 00:19:48.470
Well, you can bet that there
was an earlier synagogue,

00:19:48.470 --> 00:19:52.320
and I say that because when I wrote
the book of the food of the Jews

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:59.550
of France, the one that Mary-Jane
likes so much, when I wrote that,

00:19:59.550 --> 00:20:03.880
I realized that there were
about 150 Jewish villages

00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:05.480
or villages that had Jews.

00:20:05.480 --> 00:20:08.340
They weren't Jewish villages
in the South of France

00:20:08.340 --> 00:20:11.080
in the 1st and 2nd century AD.

00:20:11.080 --> 00:20:15.250
And these were all
destroyed, and the only thing

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:17.780
that might have been
left and then some

00:20:17.780 --> 00:20:25.400
of them would be a cemetery stone
or maybe an indentation in stone

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:28.110
where a -- what do you call it?

00:20:28.110 --> 00:20:31.970
-- a mezuzah had been
so that things --

00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:38.230
and I know that one person who
has studied Indian history a lot

00:20:38.230 --> 00:20:44.190
and has used this library a lot
at first did not agree with me.

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:45.490
And he said, you know what?

00:20:45.490 --> 00:20:48.470
You might be right, because he kept
saying unless you see an example

00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:52.010
of somebody being there, how do
you know that they were there?

00:20:52.010 --> 00:20:54.870
Well, history is a long time.

00:20:54.870 --> 00:20:58.950
And we're -- you know, a lot
of these places get floods

00:20:58.950 --> 00:21:00.850 position:56%
and all kinds of things, but anyway.

00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:04.750
And there were one -- you know,
there were hints here and there

00:21:04.750 --> 00:21:07.700
that make you realize that
of course they came there.

00:21:07.700 --> 00:21:09.980
So that was helpful to me.

00:21:09.980 --> 00:21:15.820
And then I realized that after the
destruction of the first temple,

00:21:15.820 --> 00:21:20.860
many Jews went to Babylonia.

00:21:20.860 --> 00:21:24.930
And they stayed.

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:29.940 position:56%
And so, then they went at about that
time on the Silk Route to the right.

00:21:29.940 --> 00:21:32.190
I keep saying the right
and the left.

00:21:32.190 --> 00:21:37.000
But anyway, on the Silk Route, they
went to places like Azerbaijan,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:47.320
to Georgia, to just all the way,
all the way around up into Russia

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:49.860
and eventually to Poland.

00:21:49.860 --> 00:21:53.020
So there's one group
that's going around.

00:21:53.020 --> 00:21:59.530 position:56%
Then another group went later after
the destruction of the second temple

00:21:59.530 --> 00:22:09.190
through Egypt to Rome up to
France to Italy to Spain.

00:22:09.190 --> 00:22:16.000
And then from Spain, they also went
east in the 14th and 15h century

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:21.770
through Alsace-Lorraine to
Poland and Eastern Europe.

00:22:21.770 --> 00:22:26.440
So you find a conglomeration
of people all over the place,

00:22:26.440 --> 00:22:28.930
and to me, that was
really interesting

00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:30.780
because it was reflected
in the food.

00:22:30.780 --> 00:22:36.370
So I felt that learning about Iraqi
food was very, very important.

00:22:36.370 --> 00:22:40.150
So I went to -- I couldn't
go to Iraq.

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:44.010
And what I like to do is get
stories about people and food.

00:22:44.010 --> 00:22:51.970
So I went to London, where I was
told the best Iraqi cooks are.

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:56.890
And I met with a woman named
Aileen Kolachi [assumed spelling]

00:22:56.890 --> 00:22:58.640
and who's way in her 80s.

00:22:58.640 --> 00:23:00.890
And she showed me how
to make macaroons.

00:23:00.890 --> 00:23:05.390
Macaroons started in Babylonia.

00:23:05.390 --> 00:23:07.970
Escabeche started there.

00:23:07.970 --> 00:23:12.580
You can see through people where
it wandered throughout the world.

00:23:12.580 --> 00:23:17.880
An overnight chicken
called tabit started there.

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:25.030
And people eating, you know, in the
ancient world, chicken came late

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:32.020
as far as being not -- there
were kinds of chickens, but as --

00:23:32.020 --> 00:23:33.770
the way that we eat it is --

00:23:33.770 --> 00:23:35.430
first of all, it's really late

00:23:35.430 --> 00:23:37.150
because we had the --
remember those broilers?

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:40.460
That's from about the
'30s, the smaller chickens.

00:23:40.460 --> 00:23:46.010
Bigger chickens were there, but
chickens -- hens were not eaten.

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:50.360
You would take a hen
that stopped laying eggs,

00:23:50.360 --> 00:23:52.180
because that's why you had hens.

00:23:52.180 --> 00:23:54.570
Then you would slaughter
it and eat it.

00:23:54.570 --> 00:23:59.730
You would not take a young
chicken to slaughter and eat it.

00:23:59.730 --> 00:24:04.040
And the same with cocks
were used for cock fighting.

00:24:04.040 --> 00:24:06.460
And when they were too
old for cock fighting,

00:24:06.460 --> 00:24:11.020
you would make cockova
or something like that.

00:24:11.020 --> 00:24:15.310
Now -- and the rabbis would not
allow Jews, but this is much later,

00:24:15.310 --> 00:24:18.020
to use cocks for fighting.

00:24:18.020 --> 00:24:24.570
Anyway, so there -- in
the rabbinic literature,

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:31.030 position:56%
it says that in the first century
AD the rabbis would not let Jews use

00:24:31.030 --> 00:24:35.490
chickens for cooking because they
pecked around and they were dirty.

00:24:35.490 --> 00:24:37.420
But later, of course, they did.

00:24:37.420 --> 00:24:39.830
But they let them eat
them in Babylonia.

00:24:39.830 --> 00:24:42.020
So you have this dish called tabit.

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:45.330
If I had a copy of the book, I
would read this wonderful quote.

00:24:45.330 --> 00:24:48.580
Is there -- is the book
-- there are books, right?

00:24:48.580 --> 00:24:51.760
Just give me -- thank you.

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:58.220
So the tabit was meant an
overnight cooked chicken,

00:24:58.220 --> 00:25:00.380
and I wanted to learn
how to make it.

00:25:00.380 --> 00:25:03.360
So there was this man named
Mayer Sofer [assumed spelling],

00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:07.560
who might I'm sure came to this
library who lived in Virginia.

00:25:07.560 --> 00:25:09.180
And -- thank you so much.

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:15.300
And he said to me, I will --
I'll show you how to make it.

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:18.920
So I went with him to his
house, and I went with one

00:25:18.920 --> 00:25:23.190
of the Israeli ambassadors'
wives, who wanted to go shopping

00:25:23.190 --> 00:25:25.270
in Tyson's Corner,
and I said, "Look,

00:25:25.270 --> 00:25:28.890
we'll learn to make a chicken
recipe, and then we'll go

00:25:28.890 --> 00:25:31.950
to shopping, to Bloomingdale's
or wherever."

00:25:31.950 --> 00:25:34.770
So we went to -- and she
was in her finery, right?

00:25:34.770 --> 00:25:37.730
So we walk into this man's
house, and he takes --

00:25:37.730 --> 00:25:40.600
he says to her, "Do
you know how to sew?"

00:25:40.600 --> 00:25:42.180
And she said, "Yes."

00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:48.170
And so, he had skinned the chicken
already, and she took the --

00:25:48.170 --> 00:25:52.090 position:56%
he took the skin of the chicken, and
he showed her how to make pockets

00:25:52.090 --> 00:25:54.150
that she could put the rice in.

00:25:54.150 --> 00:25:57.560 position:56%
And she really gave me a dirty look.

00:25:57.560 --> 00:26:00.520
But anyway, so she was
-- needless to say,

00:26:00.520 --> 00:26:03.510
we never got on our shopping spree.

00:26:03.510 --> 00:26:07.580
[ Laughter ]

00:26:07.580 --> 00:26:11.570
But we -- I learned this
really complicated recipe

00:26:11.570 --> 00:26:14.510
that was cooked overnight,
and it was delicious.

00:26:14.510 --> 00:26:16.510
Then I realized, well, wait
a minute, people are going

00:26:16.510 --> 00:26:17.810
to want to make this recipe.

00:26:17.810 --> 00:26:19.570
There are a lot of
quick ways to do it.

00:26:19.570 --> 00:26:22.970
So then I went to visit
Aileen Kolachi,

00:26:22.970 --> 00:26:25.940
and she showed me how she makes it.

00:26:28.370 --> 00:26:32.180
And I'll just read to you
what I learned from her,

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:35.150
which makes -- oh, my glasses.

00:26:35.150 --> 00:26:40.720
Are they right -- does anybody have
reader glasses I could just borrow?

00:26:40.720 --> 00:26:43.280
Thank you so much.

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:50.300
So -- and this is what makes doing
the kind of work I do so much fun.

00:26:50.300 --> 00:26:53.690
On a recent trip to London,

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:57.860
I visited Aileen Dangor
Kolache [assumed spelling],

00:26:57.860 --> 00:27:00.460
one of those naturally
great cooks who lives

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:03.260
in an apartment overlooking
Baker Street.

00:27:03.260 --> 00:27:07.960
Aileen, now in her late '80s,
may have left Baghdad in 1975,

00:27:07.960 --> 00:27:12.410 position:56%
but the family dishes decorated with
rosebuds and fragrant with cinnamon,

00:27:12.410 --> 00:27:16.110
cloves, nutmeg, cardamom,
and turmeric remain

00:27:16.110 --> 00:27:19.350
in her thoughts and
perfume her kitchen.

00:27:19.350 --> 00:27:22.760
During a delightful day, I learned
recipes and listened to stories

00:27:22.760 --> 00:27:27.250
about Aileen's early life when
some 20 people, mostly family,

00:27:27.250 --> 00:27:29.800
when family meant everything,

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:32.610
lived in a big house
overlooking the Tigris River.

00:27:32.610 --> 00:27:36.180
"At home we used the rice
my husband's family grew,"

00:27:36.180 --> 00:27:38.070
Aileen told me in her kitchen.

00:27:38.070 --> 00:27:40.480
"The rice often had
small stones in it,

00:27:40.480 --> 00:27:42.720
so we had to clean it
before we washed it.

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:45.310
Then we washed it again, and again.

00:27:45.310 --> 00:27:50.550
The rice we get today is clean, but
we Iraqis still wash it three times

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:52.780
and soak it for a few hours.

00:27:52.780 --> 00:27:56.480
In Baghdad, we only ate fruits
and vegetables in season,

00:27:56.480 --> 00:28:00.260
so we had to make and store what
we needed for the whole year.

00:28:00.260 --> 00:28:03.880
We even made tomato puree
for our cooking," she added.

00:28:03.880 --> 00:28:07.080
"In the summer, everybody
bought a lot of tomatoes,

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:10.620
squeezed the juice out, sieved
them to remove the seeds

00:28:10.620 --> 00:28:14.320 position:56%
and the outer skin, and put the
juice in a big container on the roof

00:28:14.320 --> 00:28:17.060
of the house and kept
it there for a few days

00:28:17.060 --> 00:28:19.680
in the sun until it became thick.

00:28:19.680 --> 00:28:23.050
Friday was the day to start tabit.

00:28:23.050 --> 00:28:26.410
There were no home ovens
at that time in Baghdad,

00:28:26.410 --> 00:28:30.810
so the tabit was cooked on charcoal
overnight for Sabbath lunch.

00:28:30.810 --> 00:28:33.840
On top of the cover, we
put eggs in their shells,

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:35.930
then covered it again," she said.

00:28:35.930 --> 00:28:39.730
"On top of everything was a
folded blanket to keep the heat.

00:28:39.730 --> 00:28:42.720
We ate the eggs Saturday
morning with tomatoes, onions,

00:28:42.720 --> 00:28:47.040
and lemon salad, with pickles
or spring onions and parsley."

00:28:47.040 --> 00:28:50.320
Today, most cooks have learned
speedier ways to make tabit

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:52.500
than the one I described above.

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:55.610
When I make it, I follow
some traditional customs

00:28:55.610 --> 00:29:00.510
like using fresh spices I grind and
cleaning the chicken with a lemon.

00:29:00.510 --> 00:29:05.650
Also, I make sure to produce
enough hakaka [assumed spelling],

00:29:05.650 --> 00:29:09.910
known in Iran as tahdig, the
prized crust of rust that forms

00:29:09.910 --> 00:29:12.100
on the bottom of the casserole.

00:29:12.100 --> 00:29:16.890
So, you know, images like that you
don't get by talking on the phone

00:29:16.890 --> 00:29:18.920
with people to get a recipe.

00:29:18.920 --> 00:29:21.990
You have to spend a
whole day at least

00:29:21.990 --> 00:29:24.060
because there's a lot
that comes out.

00:29:24.060 --> 00:29:27.220
And I did that with women in Italy.

00:29:27.220 --> 00:29:31.710
With this woman, I learned a lot of
recipes from her and other things

00:29:31.710 --> 00:29:35.090
that make what you're doing
so very, very special.

00:29:35.090 --> 00:29:40.670
And then -- and then I realized
that so much of this Iraqi food

00:29:40.670 --> 00:29:46.260
or Baghdadi food or Babylonian
food spread throughout the world,

00:29:46.260 --> 00:29:50.740
even though they had people that
came in that other conquerors,

00:29:50.740 --> 00:29:57.040
it was such a strong
commercial center that it's --

00:29:57.040 --> 00:29:59.080
when almost to the 8th century,

00:29:59.080 --> 00:30:01.720
it just was people
wanted to live there.

00:30:01.720 --> 00:30:03.200
It was a fertile region.

00:30:03.200 --> 00:30:05.640
It was a crossroads.

00:30:05.640 --> 00:30:08.800
And the Jews started something
called the Radonites [assumed

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:15.180
spelling], and the Radonites were
a group of traders that went as far

00:30:15.180 --> 00:30:21.360
as Russia, as far as China, and
they were a network of people

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:25.400
that would -- of merchants
that would start

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:28.300
with food, with buying spices.

00:30:28.300 --> 00:30:29.660
They'd buy gems.

00:30:29.660 --> 00:30:32.480
They'd buy -- I heard
they bought fish.

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:38.730
I don't know how they carried live
fish, but supposedly they did,

00:30:38.730 --> 00:30:41.350 position:56%
all the way around the world with --

00:30:41.350 --> 00:30:43.960
and it was in a way
like a relay race.

00:30:43.960 --> 00:30:48.970 position:56%
And the known verbiage -- of course,
the known language was Hebrew.

00:30:48.970 --> 00:30:53.040
But there of -- they were not
the only groups, of course.

00:30:53.040 --> 00:30:54.340
I'm just talking about one group.

00:30:54.340 --> 00:30:56.440
This -- what I'm saying
could be said about a lot

00:30:56.440 --> 00:30:59.880
of different people
within that region.

00:30:59.880 --> 00:31:03.580
But there was one thing that made
them different from everybody else,

00:31:03.580 --> 00:31:08.270
and that was their food
and their laws of religion.

00:31:08.270 --> 00:31:12.580
So for me, there are three
different ways of defining --

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:15.130
or three characteristics
of Jewish food.

00:31:15.130 --> 00:31:16.430
One of them, of course,

00:31:16.430 --> 00:31:18.750
is the dietary laws,
no question about that.

00:31:18.750 --> 00:31:22.050
Even if in the back of
your mind you don't believe

00:31:22.050 --> 00:31:24.650
in the dietary laws,
it's still there.

00:31:24.650 --> 00:31:28.440
And all the -- all the laws
of Judaism are still there.

00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:30.940
So that's number one.

00:31:30.940 --> 00:31:36.190
And also, this obsessiveness about
food, I mean believe me, it is.

00:31:36.190 --> 00:31:38.880
But I guess we're all
obsessed about food.

00:31:38.880 --> 00:31:44.860
So then the second one is this
merchant part of Judaism that just

00:31:44.860 --> 00:31:50.540
as they looked for ingredients
in India in those ancient times,

00:31:50.540 --> 00:31:53.680
Jews have always been merchants
and have always been looking

00:31:53.680 --> 00:31:57.430
for the new, maybe for the
new for themselves, the new --

00:31:57.430 --> 00:31:59.340
they've always been merchants.

00:31:59.340 --> 00:32:03.670
And that -- you can trace
that all over the world.

00:32:03.670 --> 00:32:07.540
You know, they were the first ones
to think of futures in the sense

00:32:07.540 --> 00:32:14.190
that if you buy grain when it's
first harvested and you hold it,

00:32:14.190 --> 00:32:15.860
when you buy it when
it's first harvested,

00:32:15.860 --> 00:32:17.780
there's a lot of grain, right?

00:32:17.780 --> 00:32:22.590
If you hold it to the winter,
there's not so much grain

00:32:22.590 --> 00:32:24.810
so that you can raise the prices.

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:29.350
And that's what a lot of people
in the stock exchange learned

00:32:29.350 --> 00:32:34.660
from Jewish merchants, that this
is the way things had to go.

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:37.910
The -- I just -- there are bakers.

00:32:37.910 --> 00:32:41.790
There's a disproportionate number
of bakers within Jewish communities

00:32:41.790 --> 00:32:44.790
because -- and just even
look in Washington today,

00:32:44.790 --> 00:32:48.100
Mark Furstenberg at Bread Furst.

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:52.780
And cooks, there are a lot of
Jewish chefs too right now.

00:32:52.780 --> 00:32:55.970
But I have a theory about that,
which I'll tell you later.

00:32:55.970 --> 00:33:00.200
Anyway, so the second one was the
merchant and the interest in food.

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:03.790
The third is the fact that Jews
were kicked out of so many places.

00:33:03.790 --> 00:33:08.400
So they had to adapt their cuisine
to different regions always.

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:10.480
And I think some of you
are nodding your heads.

00:33:10.480 --> 00:33:14.200
I'm sure that Indians and Lebanese
and all kinds of -- Chinese --

00:33:14.200 --> 00:33:16.240
have also had to adapt theirs.

00:33:16.240 --> 00:33:19.820
But the point is that
you want to have the --

00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:25.000
food is comfort, and you want to
have this table-centered religion

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:28.610
as comfort with the foods
that you grew up with.

00:33:28.610 --> 00:33:30.140
And I'll give you an example.

00:33:30.140 --> 00:33:34.550 position:56%
I was -- for the book, I went to El
Salvador to interview the 100 people

00:33:34.550 --> 00:33:37.730
in the Jewish community
of El Salvador.

00:33:37.730 --> 00:33:40.810
And there was this one
woman, and they all made food

00:33:40.810 --> 00:33:42.850
for me for Friday night dinner.

00:33:42.850 --> 00:33:48.280
And a woman made yucca
latkes with cilantro cream.

00:33:48.280 --> 00:33:53.560
Well, yucca is easier to get
in El Salvador than potatoes.

00:33:53.560 --> 00:33:55.540
And so, that's what she used.

00:33:55.540 --> 00:33:57.720
And, you know, and you find
that over and over again.

00:33:57.720 --> 00:34:05.200
I found escabeche, which is a fried
and marinated fish, in Jamaica.

00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:07.100
And what do they serve it with?

00:34:07.100 --> 00:34:12.870
Scotch bonnet peppers
because -- and also allspice.

00:34:12.870 --> 00:34:20.450
Now allspice too, so what I did in
this book was I took the timeline

00:34:20.450 --> 00:34:27.410
of Jewish history, and I tried
to combine it with ingredients.

00:34:27.410 --> 00:34:31.070
So when I went to Spain
and then I went

00:34:31.070 --> 00:34:33.030
to the New World, I
realized a few things.

00:34:33.030 --> 00:34:39.500
First of all, the -- 1492 being
the time when the Jews had to get

00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:42.000
out of Spain, it was no coincidence

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:48.960
that Christopher Columbus had
his boat that started in 1492

00:34:48.960 --> 00:34:53.760
because for the eight years prior
to that, all the boats were rented

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:55.590
for Jews that wanted to get out.

00:34:55.590 --> 00:34:59.780
They had a big -- there
were like 250,000 Jews

00:34:59.780 --> 00:35:02.140
in Spain, and they had a deadline.

00:35:02.140 --> 00:35:03.490
So they got out.

00:35:03.490 --> 00:35:10.370
When Christopher Columbus, well,
went, there were certainly Jews

00:35:10.370 --> 00:35:15.280
that were on the boats and
that stayed in the New World.

00:35:15.280 --> 00:35:22.710
And then they brought back or else
other people brought back to Jews

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:25.540
that were called Turkish merchants.

00:35:25.540 --> 00:35:29.600
They were originally Sephardic
merchants, but they didn't want

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:34.350
to be called Sephardic because
they knew they were being kicked

00:35:34.350 --> 00:35:35.650
out of Spain.

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:37.760
There were also Portuguese
that were called

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:40.330
in France Mershon [assumed
spelling] Portuguese,

00:35:40.330 --> 00:35:42.820
and they were Portuguese merchants

00:35:42.820 --> 00:35:45.660
that were also taking
these ingredients

00:35:45.660 --> 00:35:47.610
and bringing them to places.

00:35:47.610 --> 00:35:51.550
Well, first of all, they came to
Naples, which was a Spanish port.

00:35:51.550 --> 00:35:58.470
But then they went -- like,
corn, peppers, tomatoes,

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:01.730
and I forget what other
one, potatoes --

00:36:01.730 --> 00:36:07.200
went to places like
Bulgaria and Hungary,

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:10.120
always by the so-called
Turkish merchants.

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:14.210
And this was a fertile
area of the Danube River.

00:36:14.210 --> 00:36:16.080
So they planted them.

00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:19.690
Most of those things were used
for fodder at the beginning,

00:36:19.690 --> 00:36:23.810 position:56%
and then eventually, like Jerusalem
artichokes, people liked using them.

00:36:23.810 --> 00:36:26.550
But the potatoes, they
were just grown

00:36:26.550 --> 00:36:28.230
for farms, that's it, not to eat.

00:36:28.230 --> 00:36:32.540
And even when my father, who
came from Germany in 1929,

00:36:32.540 --> 00:36:33.890
when he came to the United States

00:36:33.890 --> 00:36:36.590
and there was all this good
corn, he wouldn't eat it.

00:36:36.590 --> 00:36:39.240
He said that's just for animals.

00:36:39.240 --> 00:36:45.280 position:56%
So I guess in Southern Germany, they
didn't have really good corn then.

00:36:45.280 --> 00:36:49.040
So I realized that -- and the
other thing that I realized

00:36:49.040 --> 00:36:54.020
in the centuries before
where foods went.

00:36:54.020 --> 00:36:59.420
Where foods went were very easy
for me to figure out their roots

00:36:59.420 --> 00:37:04.020
because you can see
there's a lot written on it.

00:37:04.020 --> 00:37:08.200
And -- but it's really
interesting to trace it,

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:10.150
and you'll see it in my book.

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:13.690
But the other thing that
was a big, big help to me,

00:37:13.690 --> 00:37:16.770
and I'm doing all this academic
stuff because this is the Library

00:37:16.770 --> 00:37:21.600
of Congress, is -- was
the Genizah in Cambridge.

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:24.950
So I went there, and
I was really lucky

00:37:24.950 --> 00:37:30.300
because then Woodwright [assumed
spelling], who was the archivist,

00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:34.710
spent a lot of time with me
telling me about the ephemera.

00:37:34.710 --> 00:37:37.410
Do you know -- does everybody
here know what the Genizah is?

00:37:37.410 --> 00:37:40.690
It's this -- you do, or you don't?

00:37:40.690 --> 00:37:49.980
Okay. So a genizah were like
a treasure chest of documents.

00:37:49.980 --> 00:37:52.360
They say they were
in Christian churches

00:37:52.360 --> 00:37:56.500
and mosques and in synagogues.

00:37:56.500 --> 00:38:00.830
And they -- they're lost
documents of ephemera mostly.

00:38:00.830 --> 00:38:04.120
But they're supposed to keep
everything that was written

00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:08.040
on sheepskin or paper with
the name of God in it.

00:38:08.040 --> 00:38:15.770 position:56%
And they found one of these treasure
chests in the Cairo synagogue

00:38:15.770 --> 00:38:18.890
in about the end of
the 19th century.

00:38:18.890 --> 00:38:22.750
And I mean it's -- there's a
wonderful book called Sacred Trash

00:38:22.750 --> 00:38:26.550
that if any of you want to
read, you'll read about the --

00:38:26.550 --> 00:38:31.910
it's a wonderful detective story
about how all this stuff was found

00:38:31.910 --> 00:38:34.690
and then how you read
about different people.

00:38:34.690 --> 00:38:38.390
And there were letters so
that I learned, for example,

00:38:38.390 --> 00:38:42.640
that there was a -- remember I
said that there's like a relay race

00:38:42.640 --> 00:38:48.350
from Aden to Cairo, or
it was called Fustat,

00:38:48.350 --> 00:38:52.310
which is part of Cairo today.

00:38:52.310 --> 00:38:56.890
And then some went to
Ceylon, these boats.

00:38:56.890 --> 00:39:01.740
And then a lot of the heads of the
boats would write these letters,

00:39:01.740 --> 00:39:06.090
and they would say -- write one
letter to another merchant saying,

00:39:06.090 --> 00:39:11.470
"I slipped in some turmeric
and other spices so that the --

00:39:11.470 --> 00:39:16.200
so you wouldn't have
to pay tariff on them."

00:39:16.200 --> 00:39:19.700
And you knew that these
were from men for,

00:39:19.700 --> 00:39:22.550
you know, the -- for virility.

00:39:22.550 --> 00:39:26.800
And it's really interesting
to see what went

00:39:26.800 --> 00:39:28.760
on just in what they wrote.

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:33.400
And this was a way of endearing
one merchant to another merchant,

00:39:33.400 --> 00:39:37.180
or there was wheat sent
to a community in Aden

00:39:37.180 --> 00:39:39.540
because they didn't
have wheat at the time.

00:39:39.540 --> 00:39:40.840
And, you know, you're supposed

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:44.020
to make a wheat challah
on Friday night.

00:39:44.020 --> 00:39:47.360
So you got senses, or
one I have in my book,

00:39:47.360 --> 00:39:51.710
a woman who was a lousy cook,
and her husband went out,

00:39:51.710 --> 00:39:57.930
and this was what you
learned what people did.

00:39:57.930 --> 00:40:03.740
He had the shopping list because
a lot of the women were kept in --

00:40:03.740 --> 00:40:06.350
they were in their
courtyards or at home.

00:40:06.350 --> 00:40:07.650
They didn't go out.

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:10.630
And it was a way of a man
saying, look, I made the money.

00:40:10.630 --> 00:40:13.580
So he would go out like on a
Wednesday because it was --

00:40:13.580 --> 00:40:15.480 position:56%
you wanted to have food for Shabbat.

00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:18.380
He would go -- when he got his
paycheck, if it was Wednesday

00:40:18.380 --> 00:40:24.070 position:56%
or Thursday, he'd come after work,
go to the market, and you can see it

00:40:24.070 --> 00:40:26.940
like in Machneyuda
in Jerusalem today.

00:40:26.940 --> 00:40:30.650
Go there, he'd buy the
ingredients that she said,

00:40:30.650 --> 00:40:32.170
and he'd bring them home.

00:40:32.170 --> 00:40:36.320
So he had this one recipe,
this man who wrote a lot

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:39.240
about his wife being
a terrible wife.

00:40:39.240 --> 00:40:41.010
But my editor made me take it out.

00:40:41.010 --> 00:40:42.310
I don't know why.

00:40:42.310 --> 00:40:45.410
Anyway, so -- but she could cook.

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:53.140
So he had this one recipe for
Shavuot, one hen for the Sabbath,

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:55.790
eggplant, and some other things.

00:40:55.790 --> 00:40:59.280
So I looked in old books because
I realized that most things --

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:04.070
you know, that people didn't
have different like a vegetable

00:41:04.070 --> 00:41:07.030
on one side, and that came later.

00:41:07.030 --> 00:41:10.040
They would have a stew pretty much.

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:13.210
That's what you would have
for your dishes, or, you know,

00:41:13.210 --> 00:41:17.820
a stew like a couscous, where
you'd have rice and you'd have --

00:41:17.820 --> 00:41:23.050 position:56%
anyway, so I looked in old, old
cookbooks for chicken with eggplant,

00:41:23.050 --> 00:41:25.360
and I had never known
that as a Sabbath dish.

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:31.400
And there it was in all
of these Iraqi cookbooks

00:41:31.400 --> 00:41:33.300
and also different
Sephardic cookbooks.

00:41:33.300 --> 00:41:39.650 position:56%
And you realize a lot of the people
that came to Spain came through Iraq

00:41:39.650 --> 00:41:45.200
so that -- and I'm convinced
that they went back to Iraq maybe

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:48.300
after 400 years because
they still --

00:41:48.300 --> 00:41:52.690 position:56%
when they were kicked out of Spain,
when they still had relatives there.

00:41:52.690 --> 00:41:54.620 position:56%
And then they went around the world.

00:41:54.620 --> 00:41:58.720
So, you know, and then
they went to India,

00:41:58.720 --> 00:42:02.730
because I met this woman named
Queenie Halegwa [assumed spelling]

00:42:04.920 --> 00:42:09.860
in Kochi, and she invited
me for dinner.

00:42:09.860 --> 00:42:11.490
And she kept talking about pastel.

00:42:11.490 --> 00:42:15.510 position:56%
And her -- and I thought, wait a
minute, this woman is not Sephardic.

00:42:15.510 --> 00:42:17.250
She's really Iraqi.

00:42:17.250 --> 00:42:19.110
And her son said the same thing.

00:42:19.110 --> 00:42:21.760
He said, "I think that
our family was in Spain.

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:23.930
They came back, but
she liked that pastel,

00:42:23.930 --> 00:42:28.960
which is like a pastry
filled with things."

00:42:28.960 --> 00:42:31.600
Oh, there are many
different kinds of pastels.

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:35.870
And then brought it back to --
hit comes in families, right,

00:42:35.870 --> 00:42:37.990
these words and these recipes.

00:42:37.990 --> 00:42:42.030
The other thing is there's no -- in
the Genizah, there are no recipes.

00:42:42.030 --> 00:42:45.120
There are shopping lists, and
then there are prescriptions

00:42:45.120 --> 00:42:47.880
from doctors, like Mimodenes
[assumed spelling] would have

00:42:47.880 --> 00:42:51.660
written you need this -- you
need chicken and chicken soup.

00:42:51.660 --> 00:42:52.960
And so they would talk

00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:56.240
about different ingredients
that you would need.

00:42:56.240 --> 00:42:59.570 position:56%
So the Genizah's really interesting.

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:01.620
So please read that.

00:43:01.620 --> 00:43:07.330
So -- and then of course, food
has changed tremendously today,

00:43:07.330 --> 00:43:14.830
and that's because
of the world of 1850s

00:43:14.830 --> 00:43:20.620
on where we have all this rich
food and the processed food.

00:43:20.620 --> 00:43:23.460
The Age of Industrialization
changed everything

00:43:23.460 --> 00:43:24.870
and changed it very quickly.

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:29.260
I'm convinced that in the ancient
world, it took a lot longer time

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:31.340
to -- for food to change.

00:43:31.340 --> 00:43:32.930
For us, it's within weeks.

00:43:32.930 --> 00:43:34.820
We've got email.

00:43:34.820 --> 00:43:41.700
We have radio, TV, cook --
how many cookbooks do we have?

00:43:41.700 --> 00:43:43.400
But it used to be that
you would learn it

00:43:43.400 --> 00:43:45.530
from your mother, from your family.

00:43:45.530 --> 00:43:47.730
In a way, it was like
the closed communities

00:43:47.730 --> 00:43:51.980
of today, but just family units.

00:43:51.980 --> 00:43:54.430
And that's -- and people would

00:43:54.430 --> 00:43:58.930
in different countries
guard their foods

00:43:58.930 --> 00:44:02.800
so preciously within the community.

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:05.990
And I've gone way beyond
